Definition 3.2 In a symmetric monoidal category with finite products $\times$ and terminal object $\mathsf{1}$, a coalgebra modality has Seely isomorphisms [3, 6, 43] if the map $\chi_{\mathsf{1}}:\oc(\mathsf{1})\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}K$ and natural transformation ${\chi:\oc(A\times B)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}\oc A\otimes\oc B}$ defined respectively as $\xymatrixcolsep{2pc}\xymatrix{\oc(\mathsf{1})\ar[r]^{-}{e}&K&\oc(A\times B)\ar% [r]^{-}{\Delta}&\oc(A\times B)\otimes\oc(A\times B)\ar[rr]^{-}{\oc(\pi_{0})% \otimes\oc(\pi_{1})}&&\oc(A)\otimes\oc(B)}$ are isomorphisms, so $\oc(\mathsf{1})\cong K$ and $\oc(A\times B)\cong\oc(A)\otimes\oc(B)$.
Definition 4.1 An additive category is a category enriched in commutative monoids, that is, a category in which each hom-set is a commutative monoid, with addition operation $+$ and zero $0$, and in which composition preserves the additive structure in the sense that $k(f+g)h=(kfh)+(kgh)$ and $0f=0=f0$. An additive symmetric monoidal category [7] is a symmetric monoidal category that is also an additive category such that the monoidal product $\otimes$ is compatible with the additive structure in the sense that $k\otimes(f+g)\otimes h=k\otimes f\otimes h+k\otimes g\otimes h$ and $f\otimes 0\otimes g=0$.
Definition 5.1 A tangent monad on a tangent category $(\mathbb{X},\mathbb{T})$ is a quadruple $(\mathsf{S},\eta,\mu,\lambda)$ consisting of a monad $(\mathsf{S},\eta,\mu)$ equipped with a distributive law $\lambda$ of the tangent functor $\mathsf{T}$ over $(\mathsf{S},\mu,\delta)$ such that the following diagrams commute: $\xymatrixcolsep{1.5pc}\xymatrixrowsep{2pc}\xymatrix{&\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}(M)% \ar[d]_{-}{\lambda_{M}}\ar[dr]^{-}{\mathsf{S}(p_{M})}&&\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}_{2% }(M)\ar[r]^{-}{\mathsf{S}(\sigma_{M})}\ar[d]|-{\langle\mathsf{S}(\rho_{0})% \lambda,\mathsf{S}(\rho_{1})\lambda\rangle}&\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}(M)\ar[d]^{-}{% \lambda_{M}}&\mathsf{S}(M)\ar[dr]_{-}{z_{\mathsf{S}(M)}}\ar[r]^{-}{\mathsf{S}(% z_{M})}&\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}(M)\ar[d]^{-}{\lambda_{M}}\\ &\mathsf{T}\mathsf{S}(M)\ar[r]_{-}{p_{\mathsf{S}(M)}}&\mathsf{S}(M)&\mathsf{T}% _{2}\mathsf{S}(M)\ar[r]_{-}{\sigma_{\mathsf{S}(M)}}&\mathsf{T}\mathsf{S}(M)&&% \mathsf{T}\mathsf{S}(M)}$ $\xymatrixcolsep{1.5pc}\xymatrixrowsep{2pc}\xymatrix{\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}(M)\ar% [dd]_{-}{\lambda_{M}}\ar[r]^{-}{\mathsf{S}(\ell_{M})}&\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}^{2}% (M)\ar[d]^{-}{\lambda_{\mathsf{T}(M)}}&&\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}^{2}(M)\ar[d]_{-}{% \lambda_{\mathsf{T}(M)}}\ar[r]^{-}{\mathsf{S}(c_{M})}&\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}^{2}% (M)\ar[d]^{-}{\lambda_{\mathsf{T}(M)}}\\ &\mathsf{T}\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}(M)\ar[d]^{-}{\mathsf{T}(\lambda_{M})}&&\mathsf% {T}\mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}(M)\ar[d]_{-}{\mathsf{T}(\lambda_{M})}&\mathsf{T}% \mathsf{S}\mathsf{T}(M)\ar[d]^{-}{\mathsf{T}(\lambda_{M})}\\ \mathsf{T}\mathsf{S}(M)\ar[r]_{-}{\ell_{\mathsf{S}(M)}}&\mathsf{T}^{2}\mathsf{% S}(M)&&\mathsf{T}^{2}\mathsf{S}(M)\ar[r]_{-}{c_{\mathsf{S}(M)}}&\mathsf{T}^{2}% \mathsf{S}(M)}$
Definition 2.1 Let $\mathbb{X}$ be a category. A tangent structure [12] $\mathbb{T}$ on $\mathbb{X}$ is a sextuple $\mathbb{T}:=(\mathsf{T},p,\sigma,z,\ell,c)$ consisting of: • An endofunctor $\mathsf{T}:\mathbb{X}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathbb{X}$; • A natural transformation $p_{M}:\mathsf{T}(M)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill% }}\limits}M$, known as the projection, such that for each $M$ and each $n\in\mathbb{N}$, there is an $n$-th fibre power4I.e, a fibered product [36] of $n$ instances of $p_{M}$ $\mathsf{T}_{n}(M)$ of $p_{M}$ (with projections $\rho_{i}:\mathsf{T}_{n}(M)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{T}(M)$), and this fibre power is preserved by $\mathsf{T}^{m}$ for each $m\in\mathbb{N}$. For each $n\in\mathbb{N}$, this induces a functor $\mathsf{T}_{n}:\mathbb{X}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathbb{X}$ where by convention $\mathsf{T}_{0}=1_{\mathbb{X}}$ and $\mathsf{T}_{1}=\mathsf{T}$. • Natural transformations ${\sigma_{M}:\mathsf{T}_{2}(M)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{T}(M)}$, known as the sum operation on tangent vectors, ${z_{M}:M\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}% \mathsf{T}(M)}$, known as the zero vector field, ${\ell_{M}:\mathsf{T}(M)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{T}^{2}(M)}$, known as the vertical lift, and $c_{M}:\mathsf{T}^{2}(M)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits}\mathsf{T}^{2}(M)$, known as the canonical flip; and such that $p$, $\sigma$, $z$, $\ell$, and $c$ satisfy the various equational axioms found in [12, 20] and that for each $M$, the following diagram is an equalizer diagram [36], known as the universality of the vertical lift: $\xymatrixcolsep{5pc}\xymatrix{\mathsf{T}_{2}(M)\ar[rr]^{-}{\langle\rho_{0}z_{% \mathsf{T}(M)},\rho_{1}\ell_{M}\rangle\mathsf{T}(\sigma_{M})}&&\mathsf{T}^{2}(% M)\ar@<+.5ex>[r]^{-}{\mathsf{T}(p_{M})}\ar@<-.5ex>[r]_{-}{p_{\mathsf{T}(M)}p_{% M}z_{M}}&\mathsf{T}(M)}$ where $\langle-,-\rangle$ is the pairing operation induced by the universal property of the pullback.
Definition 2.5 A representable tangent category [12] is a tangent category $(\mathbb{X},\mathbb{T})$ such that $\mathbb{X}$ has finite products and for each $n\in\mathbb{N}$, $\mathsf{T}_{n}$ is a representable functor, that is, $\mathsf{T}_{n}(-)\cong(-)^{D_{n}}$ for some exponent object $D_{n}$. In the case of $n=1$, the object $D_{1}$ (which we denote simply as $D$) representing the tangent functor, $\mathsf{T}(-)\cong(-)^{D}$, is called the infinitesimal object [12] of the representable tangent category $(\mathbb{X},\mathbb{T})$.
Definition 4.3 A differential storage category [7] is a differential category with finite biproducts whose coalgebra modality has the Seely isomorphisms.
Definition 2.3.1 For $G\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathfrak{R})$, $v\in\check{V}(G)$, $e\in\check{E}(G)$, define $\operatorname{inc}_{G}(v,e):=\varsigma_{G}^{-1}(v)\cap\omega_{G}^{-1}(e)$.
Definition 2.1.1 (Initial & terminal) Let $\mathbb{0}_{\mathfrak{R}}:=I^{\diamond}(\emptyset)$ and $\mathbb{1}_{\mathfrak{R}}:=I^{\star}\left(\{1\}\right)$. As $I^{\diamond}$ is cocontinuous and $\emptyset$ is initial in $\mathbf{Set}$, $\mathbb{0}_{\mathfrak{R}}$ is initial in $\mathfrak{R}$. As $I^{\star}$ is continuous and $\{1\}$ is terminal in $\mathbf{Set}$, $\mathbb{1}_{\mathfrak{R}}$ is terminal in $\mathfrak{R}$.
Definition 2.2.3 (Generated subhypergraph) Given $G\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathfrak{R})$, let $S_{1}\subseteq\check{V}(G)$, $S_{2}\subseteq\check{E}(G)$, and $T\subseteq I(G)$. Let $\xymatrix{S_{1}\ar[r]^{(}0.4){j_{1}}&\check{V}(G)},\xymatrix{S_{2}\ar[r]^{(}0.% 4){j_{2}}&\check{E}(G)}$, $\xymatrix{T\ar[r]^{(}0.4){k}&I(G)}$ be the inclusion maps. There are unique $\xymatrix{\check{V}^{\diamond}\left(S_{1}\right)\ar[r]^{(}0.6){\hat{j}_{1}}&G}% ,\xymatrix{\check{E}^{\diamond}\left(S_{2}\right)\ar[r]^{(}0.6){\hat{j}_{2}}&G% },\xymatrix{I^{\diamond}(T)\ar[r]^{(}0.6){\hat{k}}&G}$ such that $\check{V}\left(\hat{j}_{1}\right)=j_{1}$, $\check{E}\left(\hat{j}_{2}\right)=j_{2}$, $I\left(\hat{k}\right)=k$. Let $\varpi_{n}$ be the canonical inclusions into $\check{V}^{\diamond}\left(S_{1}\right)\coprod\check{E}^{\diamond}\left(S_{2}% \right)\coprod I^{\diamond}(T)$ for $n=1,2,3$. There is a unique $\xymatrix{\check{V}^{\diamond}\left(S_{1}\right)\coprod\check{E}^{\diamond}% \left(S_{2}\right)\coprod I^{\diamond}(T)\ar[r]^{(}0.8){\phi}&G}$ such that $\phi\circ\varpi_{1}=\hat{j}_{1}$, $\phi\circ\varpi_{2}=\hat{j}_{2}$, and $\phi\circ\varpi_{3}=\hat{k}$. Define the subhypergraph $\operatorname{Gen}_{G}\left(S_{1},S_{2},T\right)$ of $G$ by 1. $\check{V}\operatorname{Gen}_{G}\left(S_{1},S_{2},T\right):=\operatorname{ran}% \left(\check{V}(\phi)\right)$, 2. $\check{E}\operatorname{Gen}_{G}\left(S_{1},S_{2},T\right):=\operatorname{ran}% \left(\check{E}(\phi)\right)$, 3. $I\operatorname{Gen}_{G}\left(S_{1},S_{2},T\right):=\operatorname{ran}\left(I(% \phi)\right)$.
Definition 2.1.2 (Partial morphism representer construction) For $G\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathfrak{R})$, define an incidence hypergraph $\tilde{G}$ by 1. $\check{V}\left(\tilde{G}\right):=\left(\{1\}\times\check{V}(G)\right)\cup\left% \{(0,0)\right\}$, $\check{E}\left(\tilde{G}\right):=\left(\{1\}\times\check{E}(G)\right)\cup\left% \{(0,0)\right\}$, 2. $I\left(\tilde{G}\right):=\left(\{1\}\times I(G)\right)\cup\left(\{0\}\times% \check{V}\left(\tilde{G}\right)\times\check{E}\left(\tilde{G}\right)\right)$, 3. $\varsigma_{\tilde{G}}(a):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\left(1,\varsigma_{G}(i)% \right),&a=(1,i),\\ v,&a=(0,v,e),\\ \end{array}\right.$ $\omega_{\tilde{G}}(a):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\left(1,\omega_{G}(i)\right),% &a=(1,i),\\ e,&a=(0,v,e).\\ \end{array}\right.$ Define $\xymatrix{G\ar[r]^{\eta_{G}}&\tilde{G}}\in\mathfrak{R}$ by $\check{V}\left(\eta_{G}\right)(v):=(1,v)$, $\check{E}\left(\eta_{G}\right)(e):=(1,e)$, and $I\left(\eta_{G}\right)(i):=(1,i)$. Note that $\eta_{G}$ is monic by (borceux, , Corollary I.2.15.3).
Definition 2.2.6 (Power hypergraph) Given $G\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathfrak{R})$, define the incidence hypergraph $\operatorname{Pwr}(G)$ by 1. $\check{V}\operatorname{Pwr}(G):=\mathcal{P}\check{V}(G)$, $\check{E}\operatorname{Pwr}(G):=\mathcal{P}\check{E}(G)$, 2. $I\operatorname{Pwr}(G):=\left\{K\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathfrak{R}):K\textrm{ % is a subhypergraph of }G\right\}$, 3. $\varsigma_{\operatorname{Pwr}(G)}(K):=\check{V}(K)$, $\omega_{\operatorname{Pwr}(G)}(K):=\check{E}(K)$. Define $\xymatrix{G\prod\operatorname{Pwr}(G)\ar[r]^{(}0.7){\mathrm{elem}_{G}}&\Omega_% {\mathfrak{R}}}\in\mathfrak{R}$ by 1. $\check{V}\left(\mathrm{elem}_{G}\right)(v,S)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}(1,1),&% v\in S,\\ (0,0),&v\not\in S,\\ \end{array}\right.$, $\check{E}\left(\mathrm{elem}_{G}\right)(e,T)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}(1,1),&% e\in T,\\ (0,0),&e\not\in T,\\ \end{array}\right.$, 2. $I\left(\mathrm{elem}_{G}\right)(i,K)=\left\{\begin{array}[]{ll}(1,1),&i\in I(K% ),\\ \left(0,(1,1),(1,1)\right),&i\not\in I(K),\varsigma_{G}(i)\in\check{V}(K),% \omega_{G}(i)\in\check{E}(K),\\ \left(0,(1,1),(0,0)\right),&\varsigma_{G}(i)\in\check{V}(K),\omega_{G}(i)\not% \in\check{E}(K),\\ \left(0,(0,0),(1,1)\right),&\varsigma_{G}(i)\not\in\check{V}(K),\omega_{G}(i)% \in\check{E}(K),\\ \left(0,(0,0),(0,0)\right),&\varsigma_{G}(i)\not\in\check{V}(K),\omega_{G}(i)% \not\in\check{E}(K).\\ \end{array}\right.$
Definition 2.2.2 (Subhypergraph) Given an incidence hypergraph $G$, a subhypergraph of $G$ is an incidence hypergraph $K$ such that the following conditions hold: 1. $\check{V}(K)\subseteq\check{V}(G)$, $\check{E}(K)\subseteq\check{E}(G)$, $I(K)\subseteq I(G)$, 2. $\varsigma_{K}(i)=\varsigma_{G}(i)$, $\omega_{K}(i)=\omega_{G}(i)$ for all $i\in I(K)$. The canonical inclusion $\xymatrix{K\ar[r]^{\iota_{K}}&G}\in\mathfrak{R}$ is such that $\check{V}\left(\iota_{K}\right)$, $\check{E}\left(\iota_{K}\right)$, and $I\left(\iota_{K}\right)$ are the set-theoretic inclusions.
Definition 2.3.5 (Loading) Given an incidence hypergraph $G$, define the loading of $G$ as the incidence hypergraph $L_{\mathfrak{R}}(G)$ constructed as follows: 1. $\check{V}L_{\mathfrak{R}}(G):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\check{V}(G),&\check{V% }(G)\neq\emptyset,\\ \{0\},&\check{V}(G)=\emptyset;\\ \end{array}\right.$ $\check{E}L_{\mathfrak{R}}(G):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\check{E}(G),&\check{E% }(G)\neq\emptyset,\\ \{0\},&\check{E}(G)=\emptyset;\\ \end{array}\right.$ 2. $IL_{\mathfrak{R}}(G):=\begin{array}[]{l}\left(\{1\}\times I(G)\right)\cup\left% (\{0\}\times\left\{(v,e):\operatorname{inc}_{G}(v,e)=\emptyset\right\}\right)% \end{array},$ 3. $\varsigma_{L_{\mathfrak{R}}(G)}(a):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\varsigma_{G}(i)% ,&a=(1,i),\\ v,&a=(0,v,e),\\ \end{array}\right.$ $\omega_{L_{\mathfrak{R}}(G)}(a):=\left\{\begin{array}[]{cc}\omega_{G}(i),&a=(1% ,i),\\ e,&a=(0,v,e).\\ \end{array}\right.$ Likewise, define an incidence hypergraph homomorphism $\xymatrix{G\ar[r]^{(}0.4){j_{G}}&L_{\mathfrak{R}}(G)}\in\mathfrak{R}$ by $\check{V}\left(j_{G}\right)(v):=v$, $\check{E}\left(j_{G}\right)(e):=e$, and $I\left(j_{G}\right)(i):=(1,i)$.
Definition 3.4. Let $L$ be a frame. A monotone mapping $e\colon L\to L^{\delta}$ into a complete lattice $L^{\delta}$ is a canonical extension of $L$ if (Dense) For all $u,v\in L^{\delta}$, $u\leq v$ if, for all $\kappa\in L^{\wedge}$ and $a\in L$, satisfying $\bigwedge e[\kappa]\leq u$ and $v\leq e(a)$ implies $\bigwedge e[\kappa]\leq e(a)$. (Compact) If $\bigwedge e[\kappa]\leq e(a)$ for some $\kappa\in L^{\wedge}$ and $a\in L$, then $a\in\kappa$.
Definition 4.4. Let $(\mathscr{C},J)$ be a category endowed with a Grothendieck topology; let $\mathfrak{F}$ be a filter on $\mathscr{C}$ and let $C$ be an object of $\mathscr{C}$. (1) We shall say that $\mathfrak{F}(C)$ converges to a point $p$ of $C$ if$\mathscr{N}_{p}(C)\subseteq\mathfrak{F}(C)$. (2) The closure of a sieve $A$ on $C$ is the collection of all points $p$ of $C$ such that every cover-neighborhood of $p$ meets $A$. (3) A point $p$ of $C$ is a cluster point of $\mathfrak{B}(C)$, the image under the filter base $\mathfrak{B}$ of $C$, if it lies in the closure of all the sieves on $\mathfrak{B}(C)$. (4) A point $p$ of $C$ is a cluster point of $\mathfrak{F}(C)$, the image under the filter $\mathfrak{F}$ of $C$, if it lies in the closure of all the sieves on $\mathfrak{F}(C)$.
Definition 4.1. Let $(\mathscr{C},J)$ be a category endowed with a Grothendieck topology, and let $C$ be an object of $\mathscr{C}$. (1) A sieve $V$ in $J(C)$, is said to be a $\mathfrak{G}$-neighborhood (short for “Grothendieck-neighborhood”) of a point $p_{\scriptscriptstyle C}$ of $C$ if there exist a morphism $\phi:D\rightarrow C$ in $V$ and a point $q:1\rightarrow D$ such that the diagram ${D}$${C}$${1}$ is commutative. (2) A sieve $V$ in $J(C)$, is said to be a $\mathfrak{G}$-neighborhood of a sieve $T$ on $C$ if $T\subseteq V$.
Definition 3.5. A basis of a filter on a category $\mathscr{C}$ is a function $\mathfrak{B}$ which assigns to each object $C$ of $\mathscr{C}$ and collection $\mathfrak{B}(C)$ of sieves on $\mathscr{C}$, in such a way that ($B_{1})$ The intersection of two sieves of $\mathfrak{B}(C)$ contains a sieve of $\mathfrak{B}(C)$; $(B_{2})$ $\mathfrak{B}(C)$ is not empty, and the empty sieve is not in $\mathfrak{B}(C)$.
Definition 3.8. An ultrafilter on a category $\mathscr{C}$ is a filter $\mathfrak{U}$ such that there is no filter on $\mathscr{C}$ which is strictly finer than $\mathfrak{U}$..
Definition 4.2. Let $(\mathscr{C},J)$ be a category endowed with a Grothendieck topology. A cover-neighborhood of $(\mathscr{C},J)$ is a function $\mathcal{N}$ which assigns to each object $(C,J(C))$ of $(\mathscr{C},J)$ and to each point $p_{\scriptscriptstyle C}$ of $C$, a collection $\mathcal{N}_{\scriptstyle p_{{}_{\scriptscriptstyle C}}}(C)\,\ \text{of sieves% of}\,\ \mathscr{C}$ such that each sieve in $\mathcal{N}_{\scriptstyle p_{{}_{\scriptscriptstyle C}}}(C)$ contains a $\mathfrak{G}$-neighborhood of $p_{\scriptscriptstyle C}$.
Definition 3.7. Given two filters $\mathfrak{F}_{1}$, $\mathfrak{F}_{2}$ on the same category $\mathscr{C}$, $\mathfrak{F}_{2}$ is said to be finer than $\mathfrak{F}_{1}$, or $\mathfrak{F}_{1}$ is coarser than $\mathfrak{F}_{2}$, if $\mathfrak{F}_{1}(C)\subseteq\mathfrak{F}_{2}(C)$ for all $C$ object of $\mathscr{C}$.
Definition 3.1. A filter on a category $\mathscr{C}$ is a function $\mathfrak{F}$ which assigns to each object $C$ of $\mathscr{C}$ a collection $\mathfrak{F}(C)$ of sieves on $\mathscr{C}$, in such a way that ($F_{1}$) If $S\in\mathfrak{F}(C)$ and $R$ is a sieve on $C$ such that $S\subseteq R$, then $R\in\mathfrak{F}(C)$; ($F_{2}$) every finite intersection of sieves of $\mathfrak{F}(C)$ belongs to $\mathfrak{F}(C)$; ($F_{3}$) the empty sieve is not in $\mathfrak{F}(C)$.
Definition 3.3. A filter subbase on a category $\mathscr{C}$ is a function $\mathfrak{S}$ which assigns to each object $C$ of $\mathscr{C}$ a collection $\mathfrak{S}(C)$ of sieves on $\mathscr{C}$, in such a way that no finite subcollection of $\mathfrak{S}(C)$ has an empty intersection.
Definition 6.2. Let $(A,C)$ and $(B,D)$ be classical relative PCAs and let $f\colon(A,C)\to(B,D)$ be an applicative morphism. We say that $f$ is computationally dense if there exists an $\mathsf{m}\in D$ such that for all $s\in D$, there exists an $r\in C$ with: $\mbox{for all }a\in A,\mbox{ if }s\cdot f(a)\!\downarrow,\mbox{ then }ra\!% \downarrow,\mathsf{m}\cdot f(ra)\!\downarrow\mbox{ and }\mathsf{m}\cdot f(ra)% \subseteq s\cdot f(a).$ Here we have written $f(a)$ for the set of $b$ such that $f(a,b)$, and an expression such as $d\cdot f(a)$ denotes $\{db\mid b\in f(a)\}$. $\lozenge$
Definition 2.3. Let $A$ be a PAS. (i) We write $\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$ for the set of inhabited subobjects of $A$, that is, the set of subobjects $U\subseteq A$ such that $\models\exists x:A\hskip 1.0pt(U(x))$, or equivalently, $U\to 1$ is regular epi. (ii) (Cf. [Ste13], Definition 1.2.4.) Let $t(\vec{x},y)$ be a term. We say that $U\in\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$ realizes $\lambda\vec{x}.t$ if: – $U(r)\models_{r,\vec{a}:A}r\vec{a}\!\downarrow$, and – $t(\vec{a},b)\!\downarrow\wedge\ U(r)\models_{r,\vec{a},b:A}r\vec{a}b\!% \downarrow\wedge\ r\vec{a}b=t(\vec{a},b)$. (Here the tuple $\vec{a}$ has the same length as $\vec{x}$.) $\lozenge$
Definition 2.5. The set $\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$ is always a filter, and it is clearly the largest possible filter. We call this filter the maximal filter on $A$. If this filter is combinatorially complete, we say that $A$ is an absolute PCA. $\lozenge$
Definition 2.13. Let $(A,\phi)$ be a PCA. (i) An assembly $X$ over $(A,\phi)$ is a pair $(|X|,E_{X})$, where $|X|$ is an object of $\mathcal{C}$ and $E_{X}$ is a total relation between $|X|$ and $A$. More explicitly, $E_{X}$ is a subobject of $|X|\times A$ such that $\models_{x:|X|}\exists a:A\hskip 1.0pt(E_{X}(x,a))$, or equivalently, the projection $E_{X}\to|X|$ is regular epi. (ii) Let $X$ and $Y$ be assemblies. A morphism of assemblies $X\to Y$ is an arrow $f\colon|X|\to|Y|$ for which there exists a $U\in\phi$ such that $E_{X}(x,a)\wedge U(r)\models_{x:|X|;r,a:A}ra\!\downarrow\wedge\ E_{Y}(f(x),ra)$ holds. We say that such a $U$ tracks $f\colon X\to Y$ $\lozenge$
Definition 2.6. (Cf. [Ste13], Definition 2.4.1.) More generally, we may select a privileged set $C$ consisting of global sections of $A$ that is closed under application: if $a,b\in C$ and $ab\!\downarrow$, then $ab\in C$. Then $\phi_{C}=\{U\subseteq A\mid\exists a\in C\ (a\subseteq U)\}$ is a filter, called the filter generated by $C$. We say that such a filter is generated by singletons. This filter is combinatorially complete if and only if for every term $t(\vec{x})$, there is an element from $C$ that realizes $\lambda\vec{x}.t$. We also write $(A,C)$ instead of $(A,\phi_{C})$. $\lozenge$
Definition 3.1. (Cf. [Ste13], Definition 2.3.20.) Let $(B,\psi)$ be a PCA and let $A$ be an object of $\mathcal{C}$. (i) If $f,f^{\prime}\subseteq A\times B$, then we say that $f\leq f^{\prime}$ if there exists a $U\in\phi$ such that $f(a,b)\wedge U(r)\models_{a:A;r,b:B}rb\!\downarrow\wedge\ f^{\prime}(a,rb).$ We say that such a $U$ realizes the inequality $f\leq f^{\prime}$. (ii) Suppose that $A$ is equipped with a partial applicative structure. A relation $f\subseteq A\times B$ is an applicative premorphism $A\to(B,\psi)$ if: (a) $f$ is total, i.e., $\models_{a:A}\exists b:B\hskip 1.0pt(f(a,b))$; (b) there exists a $U\in\psi$ such that $f(a,b)\wedge f(a^{\prime},b)\wedge aa^{\prime}\!\downarrow\wedge\ U(r)\models_% {a,a^{\prime}:A;r,b,b^{\prime}:B}rbb^{\prime}\!\downarrow\wedge f(aa^{\prime},% rbb^{\prime}).$ A set $U$ as in item (b) is said to track the applicative premorphism $f\colon A\to(B,\psi)$. (iii) Suppose that $(A,\phi)$ is a PCA. We say that a relation $f\subseteq A\times B$ is an applicative premorphism $(A,\phi)\to(B,\psi)$ if it is one $A\to(B,\psi)$. The relation $f$ is called an applicative morphism if it is an applicative premorphism, and moreover: (c) if $U\in\phi$, then $f(U):=\{b\in B\mid\exists a:A\hskip 1.0pt(U(a)\wedge f(a,b))\}\in\psi$. $\lozenge$
Definition 6.4. Let $(p,f)\colon(A,\phi)\to(B,\psi)$ be an applicative morphism. (i) $(p,f)$ is called quasi-surjective if there exists an $\mathsf{N}\in\psi$ such that for all $U\in\psi$, there exists a $V\in\phi$ satisfying $\mathsf{N}\cdot f(p(V))\!\downarrow$ and $\mathsf{N}\cdot f(p(V))\subseteq U$. (ii) Now suppose that the underlying category $\mathcal{D}$ of $(B,\psi)$ is a topos. Then $(p,f)$ is called computationally dense if there exists an $\mathsf{M}\in\psi$ such that for all $U\in\psi$, there exists a $V\in\phi$ such that $V\!A\!\downarrow$ and $\mathcal{D}\models\forall r,a:p(A)\hskip 1.0pt(p(V)(r)\wedge U\cdot f(a)\!% \downarrow\ \to\mathsf{M}\cdot f(ra)\subseteq U\cdot f(a)),$ where $U\cdot f(a)\!\downarrow$ abbreviates the formula $\forall u,b:B\hskip 1.0pt(U(u)\wedge f(a,b)\to ub\!\downarrow)$, and $\mathsf{M}\cdot f(ra)\subseteq U\cdot f(a)$ abbreviates $\forall m,b:B\hskip 1.0pt(\mathsf{M}(m)\wedge f(ra,b)\to(mb\!\downarrow\wedge% \ \exists u,b^{\prime}:B\hskip 1.0pt(U(u)\wedge f(a,b^{\prime})\wedge ub^{% \prime}\!\downarrow\wedge\ ub^{\prime}=mb))).$ We say that such $\mathsf{N}$ and $\mathsf{M}$ witness the quasi-surjectivity resp. the computational density of $(p,f)$. $\lozenge$
Definition 2.4. (Cf. [Ste13], Definition 1.3.14.) Let $A$ be a PAS. (i) We make $\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$ into a PAS over $\mathsf{Set}$ in the following way. For $U,V\in\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$, we say that $UV\!\downarrow$ if $U\times V\subseteq D$. In this case, $UV$ is the image of $U\times V\subseteq D\to A$, which is again an element of $\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$. (ii) A filter $\phi$ on $A$ is a subset of $\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$ satisfying the following two conditions: – $\phi$ is upwards closed, i.e., if $U\subseteq V$ and $U\in\phi$, then $V\in\phi$; – $\phi$ is closed under application, i.e., if $U,V\in\phi$ and $UV\!\downarrow$, then $UV\in\phi$. (iii) A set $G\subseteq\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$ is called combinatorially complete if, for every term $t(\vec{x})$, there exists a $U\in G$ realizing $\lambda\vec{x}.t$. (iv) If $\phi$ is a combinatorially complete filter on $A$, then $(A,\phi)$ is called a (relative) partial combinatory algebra over $\mathcal{C}$ (PCA). $\lozenge$
Definition 2.8. Let $A$ be a PAS, let $t(y_{0},\ldots,y_{m-1},x_{0},\ldots,x_{n})$ be a term, and let $\vec{U}=U_{0},\ldots,U_{m-1}$ be from $\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$. If $V\in\mathcal{P}^{\ast}A$, then we say that $V$ realizes $\lambda\vec{x}.t(\vec{U},\vec{x})$ if there exists a $W$ realizing $\lambda\vec{y}\hskip 1.0pt\vec{x}.t$ such that $V\subseteq W\vec{U}$. $\lozenge$
Definition 3.13. The 2-category $\mathsf{PCA}$ is defined as follows. (i) The objects are triples $(\mathcal{C},A,\phi)$, where $(A,\phi)$ is a PCA over the regular category $\mathcal{C}$. We will usually just write $(A,\phi)$ instead of $(\mathcal{C},A,\phi)$. (ii) If $(A,\phi)$ and $(B,\psi)$ are PCAs over $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ respectively, then an arrow $(A,\phi)\to(B,\psi)$ is a pair $(p,f)$, where $p\colon\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ is a regular functor and $f\colon p^{\ast}(A,\phi)\to(B,\psi)$ is an applicative morphism; (iii) A 2-cell $(p,f)\Rightarrow(q,g)$ is a natural transformation $\mu\colon p\Rightarrow q$ such that $f\leq g\circ\overline{\mu_{A}}$. An arrow of $\mathsf{PCA}$ is also called an applicative morphism, whereas a 2-cell is called an applicative transformation. $\lozenge$
Definition 6.3. Let $(A,C)$ and $(B,D)$ be classical relative PCAs and let $f\colon(A,C)\to(B,D)$ be an applicative morphism. We say that $f$ is quasi-surjective if there exists an $\mathsf{m}\in D$ such that for all $s\in D$, there exists an $r\in C$ with $\mathsf{n}\cdot f(r)=s$. (I.e., $\mathsf{n}b$ is defined and equal to $s$, for every $b\in f(r)$.) $\lozenge$
Definition 2.1. A partial applicative structure over $\mathcal{C}$ (PAS) is an inhabited object $A$ of $\mathcal{C}$ equipped with a partial binary map $A\times A\rightharpoonup A$, called application. Explicitly, the application map is given by a subobject $D\subseteq A\times A$ and an arrow $D\to A\colon(a,b)\mapsto a\cdot b$. $\lozenge$
Definition 4.5. A morphism of assemblies $f\colon X\to Y$ is called prone if the naturality square $\tikzcd[columnsep=large]X\arrow[r,"f"]\arrow[d,"\eta_{X}"^{\prime}]&Y\arrow[d,% "\eta_{Y}"]\\ \nabla\Gamma X\arrow[r,"\nabla\Gamma f"^{\prime}]&\nabla\Gamma Y$ is a pullback square. $\lozenge$
Definition 1.1. A partial combinatory algebra (PCA) is a nonempty set $A$ equipped with a partial binary map $A\times A\rightharpoonup A\colon(a,b)\mapsto ab$, called application, for which there exist $\mathsf{k},\mathsf{s}\in A$ such that (i) $(\mathsf{k}a)b$ is defined and equal to $a$; (ii) $(\mathsf{s}a)b$ is defined; (iii) if $(ac)(bc)$ is defined, then $((\mathsf{s}a)b)c$ is defined and equal to $(ac)(bc)$, for all $a,b,c\in A$. $\lozenge$
Definition 4.1. (i) Let $(p,f)\colon(A,\phi)\to(B,\psi)$ be an applicative morphism. We define $\mathsf{Asm}(p,f)$ as the functor $F\colon\mathsf{Asm}(A,\phi)\to\mathsf{Asm}(B,\psi)$ determined by: – $|FX|=p(|X|)$; – $E_{FX}=f\circ p(E_{X})=\{(x,b)\in p(|X|)\times B\mid\exists a:p(A)\hskip 1.0pt% (p(E_{X})(x,a)\wedge f(a,b))\}$; – $Fg=p(g)$. (ii) If $\mu\colon(p,f)\Rightarrow(q,g)$ is an applicative transformation, then define $\mathsf{Asm}(\mu)\colon\mathsf{Asm}(p,f)\Rightarrow\mathsf{Asm}(q,g)$ by $\mathsf{Asm}(\mu)_{X}=\mu_{|X|}$ for $X\in\mathsf{Asm}(A,\phi)$. $\lozenge$
Definition 5.5. If $(A,\phi)$ is a PCA and $I$ is an assembly, then we denote the PCA $(|I|^{\ast}(A),\phi_{I})$ by $(A,\phi)/I$. $\lozenge$
Definition 2.2. The set of terms is defined recursively by: (i) every variable is a term; (ii) if $s$ and $t$ are terms, then $(s\cdot t)$ is a term as well. $\lozenge$
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{R}$ be a small preadditive category. An $FI$-module over $\mathcal{R}$ is a functor from $FI$ to $Mod-\mathcal{R}$. For any such $\mathscr{V}:FI\longrightarrow Mod-\mathcal{R}$, we set $\mathscr{V}_{n}:=\mathscr{V}(n)=\mathscr{V}([n])$ for each $n\geq 0$. For any morphism $\phi:S\longrightarrow T$ in $FI$, we denote by $\phi_{*}:\mathscr{V}(S)\longrightarrow\mathscr{V}(T)$ the induced morphism $\mathscr{V}(\phi)$. The category of $FI$-modules over $\mathcal{R}$ will be denoted by $FI_{\mathcal{R}}$.
Definition 3.9. Let $\mathscr{V}\in FI_{\mathcal{R}}$. Then, we will say that $\mathscr{V}$ is shift finitely generated if there exists $d\geq 0$ such that $\mathbb{S}^{d}\mathscr{V}$ is finitely generated. The full subcategory of shift finitely generated objects will be denoted by $FI^{sfg}_{\mathcal{R}}$.
Definition 4.1. (see, for instance, [16, Definition III.2.2]) Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a Grothendieck category and let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Serre subcategory. Then: (1) A morphism $u:A\longrightarrow B$ in $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be a $\mathcal{C}$-isomorphism if both $Ker(u)$ and $Coker(u)$ lie in $\mathcal{C}$. (2) An object $L$ in $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be $\mathcal{C}$-closed if for every $\mathcal{C}$-isomorphism $u:A\longrightarrow B$ in $\mathcal{A}$, the induced morphism $Hom(u,L):Hom(B,L)\longrightarrow Hom(A,L)$ is an isomorphism. (3) A morphism $f:A\longrightarrow A_{\mathcal{C}}$ in $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be a $\mathcal{C}$-envelope if $f$ is a $\mathcal{C}$-isomorphism and $A_{\mathcal{C}}$ is $\mathcal{C}$-closed.
Definition 2.2. Fix $d\geq 0$. An $FI$-module $\mathscr{V}$ is said to be generated in degree $\leq d$ if there exists a (not necessarily finite) collection $\{f_{i}|i\in I\}\subseteq\underset{e\leq d}{\coprod}\textrm{ }\underset{r\in% \mathcal{R}}{\coprod}\mathscr{V}(e)(r)$ having the property that any subobject $\mathscr{V}^{\prime}\subseteq\mathscr{V}$ such that $\{f_{i}|i\in I\}\subseteq el(\mathscr{V}^{\prime})$ must satisfy $\mathscr{V}^{\prime}=\mathscr{V}$.
Definition 2.24 (Subfactorization). We call $(\mathscr{P}_{2,+},\mathscr{P}_{2,-},\mathfrak{F}_{s},tr_{2,+},tr_{2,-})$ the fusion bialgebra of the subfactor $\mathcal{N}\subset\mathcal{M}$. We say a fusion bialgebra $(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})$ can be subfactorized, if it comes from a subfactor $\mathcal{N}\subset\mathcal{M}$ in this way. We call $\mathcal{N}\subset\mathcal{M}$ a subfactorization of the fusion bialgebra.
Definition 6.10. Let $(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B},\mathfrak{F},d,\tau)$ be a fusion bialgebra. An element $x\in\mathcal{B}$ is said to be extremal if $\|\mathfrak{F}^{-1}(x)\|_{\infty,\mathcal{A}}=\|x\|_{1,\mathcal{B}}$. An element $x\in\mathcal{A}$ is said to be extremal if $\|\mathfrak{F}(x)\|_{\infty,\mathcal{B}}=\|x\|_{1,\mathcal{A}}$.
Definition 6.1 (Fusion subalgebra). Let $(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B},\mathfrak{F},d,\tau)$ be a fusion bialgebra. A subalgebra $\mathcal{A}_{0}$ of $\mathcal{A}$ is a fusion subalgebra if $(\mathcal{A}_{0},\mathfrak{F}(\mathcal{A}_{0}),\mathfrak{F},d,\tau)$ is a fusion bialgebra.
Definition 2.37. A fusion bialgebra $(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B},\mathfrak{F},d,\tau)$ is called self-dual, if its dual $(\mathcal{B},\mathcal{A},\widetilde{\mathfrak{F}},\tau,d)$ is a fusion bialgebra and they are isomorphic. Furthermore, it is called symmetrically self-dual, if $\Phi_{\mathcal{B}}\Phi_{\mathcal{A}}=1$ on $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 7.8. Let $\mathfrak{A}$ be a fusion ring of basis $\{x_{1}=1,\dots,x_{r}\}$ with $d(x_{1})\leq d(x_{2})\leq\cdots\leq d(x_{r})$. Let us call $r$ its rank, $\sum_{i}d(x_{i})^{2}$ its global dimension (or $gdim(\mathfrak{A})$), and $[d(x_{1}),d(x_{2}),\dots,d(x_{r})]$ its type, which will also be written by $[[n_{1},m_{1}],[n_{2},m_{2}],\dots,[n_{s},m_{s}]]$ where $m_{i}$ is the number of $x_{j}$ with $d(x_{j})=n_{i}$, $\sum_{i}m_{i}=r$ and $n_{1}<n_{2}<\cdots<n_{s}$.
Definition 2.8. For any $1\leq t\leq\infty$, the $t$-norms on $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ are defined as follows: $\displaystyle\|x\|_{t,\mathcal{A}}=d(|x|^{t})^{1/t},\ x\in\mathcal{A},\quad\|x% \|_{t,\mathcal{B}}=\tau(|x|^{t})^{1/t},\ x\in\mathcal{B},\quad 1\leq t<\infty$ and $\displaystyle\|x\|_{\infty,\mathcal{A}}=\sup_{1\leq j\leq m}\frac{d(x\diamond x% _{j})}{d(x_{j})},\quad\|x\|_{\infty,\mathcal{B}}=\sup_{\|y\|_{2,\mathcal{B}}=1% }\|xy\|_{2,\mathcal{B}},$
Definition 2.32 (Contragredient). For any $x\in\mathcal{A}$, we define its contragredient as $\displaystyle\overline{x}:=$ $\displaystyle\widetilde{\mathfrak{F}}\mathfrak{F}(x)\;.$ For any $y\in\mathcal{B}$, we define its contragredient as $\displaystyle\overline{y}:=$ $\displaystyle\mathfrak{F}\widetilde{\mathfrak{F}}(y)\;.$
